<br>
An employee is employed at the will of the employer for as little or as long as the private employer wishes, and in whatever lawful capacity the employer requires. Likewise, the employee may choose to work at the employee's will for the length of time he or she desires.<br>
 <br>
An employer need not provide any reason for termination of an "at will" employee, so long as the termination isn’t unlawful or <b>discriminatory</b> (based on age, sex, national origin and <b>disability</b>). Termination can be due to a merger, workforce reduction, change in company direction and business focus, poor company performance or other reasons. <br>
<br>
Also,<br>
<br>
Texas Is An Employment At Will State<br>
The right of employers to fire employees is coming under judicial scrutiny. Currently, Texas permits its employers to terminate employees at any time, for any reason or for no reason at all. Known as the employment "at will," this doctrine has been the law in Texas for over 100 years. Now, this unfettered right is being chipped away making room for exceptions which prevent employers from discharging employees without good cause. <br>
<br>
Restrictions On Firing<br>
Texas has laws which make it illegal for an employer to fire an employee for exercising a right or for reporting activities dangerous to the public. Employee activities which are protected include: <br>
<br>
Discrimination: protecting employees from retaliation for filing a claim against an employer for discrimination on the basis of race, color, religion, sex, age, national origin or disability. <br>
Workers Compensation: employees cannot be fired for filing workers compensation claims. <br>
Union Membership: employers cannot punish or fire an employee on the basis of union membership. <br>
Jury Service: employers may not terminate an employee who fails to report to work due to jury service. <br>
Military Service: employees called into military service are protected. <br>
Likewise, employees may not be fired for refusing to perform an illegal act. Employees do not have to know whether the act is, in fact, illegal. The employee need only merely have a good faith belief that the requested act is illegal. Moreover, employees may not be fired for merely seeking advice as to the illegality or illegality of a particular act. Of course, employers can avoid liability for claims of wrongful discharge if they can prove that the employee's refusal to commit the illegal act was not the sole reason for the termination. <br>
<br>
